<p>I tried to define a class and override the tilde operator:</p>  <pre><code>class foo:     def __invert__(self, other)         return 1232 # a random number , just as test </code></pre>  <p>Then calling it like:</p>  <pre><code>&gt;&gt;&gt; f = foo() &gt;&gt;&gt; g = foo() &gt;&gt;&gt; f ~ g   File "&lt;input&gt;", line 1     f ~ g       ^ SyntaxError: invalid syntax </code></pre>  <p>Can we replace the tilde operator  with a binary one so we can do  an operation like <code>f ~ g</code> without raising a syntax error.</p>